Rating: 3
My husband and I loved this-- a great, fast weeknight dinner! I am rating the dish 3.5 stars with the additions that I made. I wanted to add some more protein, so I sauteed chicken breast strips in the bacon grease (added S&P), and then followed the previous reviewers' advice & added some white onions (about 1/3 C), 2 garlic cloves (finely diced), and white mushrooms (used 5) to the zucchini/corn mixture, and then sauteed all of that in the rest of the bacon grease for a couple minutes. I also added a fresh heirloom tomato (diced) at the end for more veggies, some salt (I don't add as much salt to my pasta as this recipe calls for), and lots of parmigiano! I also used less pesto than called for (probably about 3 oz/4 large spoonfuls) so that it wouldn't overpower the bacon (I didn't have 6 slices--only 3). Also used penne instead of fusilli since that's what I had on hand. We loved it and will definitely make again--would use all 6 slices of bacon if I have it, and probably add 2 more cloves of garlic, but other than that it was definitely a make-again recipe! I have a Moosewood Cookbook recipe for a lowfat pesto that uses tomatoes in place of the oil and most of the pinenuts, so I might try that next time...I think the extra tomato flavor would go nicely with this dish. Thanks for a great quick meal!

Rating: 4
I love this recipe. It's fast and easy and makes the best of seasonal produce. I made it several times last summer, using the suggestion to fry the veggies in the bacon grease. Result: wonderful. However, I just made it for the first time this year using a different brand of jarred pesto that I hadn't realized was much wetter (more oil) than last year's jar. Result: still yummy... but greasy. I hadn't changed anything else about the recipe, so next time I'm going to try boiling the veggies with the pasta like the recipe suggests when I use the oilier pesto. In short: I suggest that if your pesto is thick and dry (doesn't run off the spoon), saute the veggies with the bacon. If your pesto is thin and oily, don't.

